        <div class="jumbotron">
            <h1>Character Classes in Regular Expressions</h1>
            <p>Character classes in regular expressions allow you to match any one of a set of characters. They are defined using square brackets ([]).</p>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <h2>Common Character Classes</h2>
                <p>Here are some commonly used character classes in regular expressions:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>\d</code> matches any digit character.</li>
                    <li><code>\w</code> matches any word character (alphanumeric + underscore).</li>
                    <li><code>\s</code> matches any whitespace character (space, tab, newline, etc.).</li>
                    <li><code>[0-9a-fA-F]</code> matches a hexadecimal digit.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <h2>Usage</h2>
                <p>Character classes are useful when you want to match any character from a specific set. They can be combined with other regex elements for more complex patterns.</p>
                <p>For example, <code>[0-9]</code> matches any digit character, and <code>[a-zA-Z]</code> matches any uppercase or lowercase letter.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-12">
                <h2>Example: <code>[aeiou]</code></h2>
                <p>This regular expression will match any single lowercase vowel character.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>[aeiou]</code> matches "a", "e", "i", "o", "u".</li>
                    <li><code>[aeiou]</code> does not match "b", "c", "d", etc.</li>
                </ul>
                <h2>Example: <code>[1234]</code></h2>
                <p>This regular expression will match any number in the bracket.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>[1234]</code> matches "1", "2", "3", "4".</li>
                    <li><code>[1234]</code> does not match "5", "6", "7", etc.</li>
                </ul>
                <h2>Example: <code>[CcDdTt]o[NnMmDd]e</code></h2>
                <p>This regular expression will match lowercase and uppercase characters and find a word.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><code>[CcDdTt]o[NnMmDd]e</code> matches "Code", "Come", "Tone", "doNe".</li>
                    <li><code>[CcDdTt]o[NnMmDd]e</code> does not match "Rope", "MoLe", "Zone", etc.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
